'''Erskine Anton Norris''' (born 7 January 1940 in Kirtons, [[Saint Philip, Barbados|Saint Philip]], [[Barbados]]) is a former [[Barbados|Barbadian]] [[high jump]]er.
==Athletic career== Norris first represented Barbados at the [[Athletics at the 1962 Central American and Caribbean Games|1962 Central American and Caribbean Games]] in [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], [[Jamaica]] where he won silver in [[Athletics at the 1962 Central American and Caribbean Games – Men's high jump|high jump]] with a jump of 1.98 metres. Three months later at the [[Athletics at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in [[Perth]], [[Australia]], Norris won bronze in the [[Athletics at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games – Men's high jump|high jump]] clearing the bar at {{height|ft=6|in=8|precision=2}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Results of the men's high jump at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|url=http://www.thecgf.com/games/results.asp?gameid=3035&sportid=1471|publisher=[[Commonwealth Games Federation|CGF]]|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref> In doing so, he became the first athlete to win a bronze medal for Barbados and the first athlete to win a medal of any colour in a sport besides weightlifting for Barbados at the Commonwealth Games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbados - Medals Tally by Games|url=http://www.thecgf.com/countries/tally.asp?countryid=9|publisher=[[Commonwealth Games Federation|CGF]]|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref> The following year, Norris was part of the inaugural contingent to represent Barbados at the [[Athletics at the 1963 Pan American Games|1963 Pan American Games]] in [[São Paulo]], [[Brazil]]. There he won one of the first medals for his country, bronze in [[Athletics at the 1963 Pan American Games – Men's high jump|high jump]]. In 1966, he repeated his performance of four year prior in taking the silver medal at the [[Athletics at the 1966 Central American and Caribbean Games|San Juan Central American and Caribbean Games]] in the [[Athletics at the 1966 Central American and Caribbean Games – Men's high jump|high jump]] and the bronze in [[Athletics at the 1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games – Men's high jump|high jump]] at the [[Athletics at the 1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|Kingston British Empire and Commonwealth Games]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Results of the men's high jump at the 1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|url=http://www.thecgf.com/games/results.asp?gameid=3036&sportid=1471|publisher=[[Commonwealth Games Federation|CGF]]|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>
Norris was also a [[cricket]]er who played in one [[first-class cricket]] match for [[Barbados national cricket team|Barbados]] in February 1963 against [[British Guiana national cricket team|British Guiana]]. Norris, selected in the team is a right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast bolwer]], took no wickets in the match which British Guiana won by 34 runs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbados v British Guiana |subscription=yes |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/25/25956.html|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>
==Business career== Norris holds a [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] degree in Management and International Business from [[New York University]] [[New York University Stern School of Business|Graduate School of Business Administration]], and a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree with honours in Economics and Business Administration from the [[Interamerican University of Puerto Rico]].
Norris has worked in business development for most of his career, while a senior executive of the Barbados Investment and Development Corporation, where he served as a Divisional Director and acting CEO. He was also Director of the Corporation's North American Operations, based in New York. He has assisted the promotion, start-up and development of a large number of local and international businesses and successfully implemented several technical assistance initiatives.
As a consultant, Anton also served as Regional Technical Advisor to the Investment Promotion and Export Development (IPED) Project, in the Economic Affairs Secretariat of the [[Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States]], under the aegis of the [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID). As of March 2009, Norris was an associate consultant of May Hinds Consulting.<ref>{{cite journal|title=E. Anton Norris, MBA|journal=Our Consulting Practice - A Profile|url=http://www.onecaribbean.org/content/files/MAYHINDSConsulting.pdf|pages=[http://www.onecaribbean.org/content/files/MAYHINDSConsulting.pdf#page=14 pp. 14–15]|format=pdf|publisher=May Hinds Consulting Inc.|date=March 2009}}</ref>
